In the last few days, Russian troops have launched an offensive in Ukraine=
=E2=80=99s Kharkiv region, advancing around 5 kilometers and seizing a few =
border villages along the way. None of this is surprising: Ukrainian forces=
 have been shelling the neighboring Russian region of Belgorod for months, =
and Russian officials have been openly discussing creating a buffer zone to=
 protect the territory and its residents. Troops have been massing on the R=
ussian side for weeks. The only thing left was for Vladimir Putin to approv=
e the order to move in.

The Kharkiv offensive is likely designed to achieve two parallel political =
and tactical goals. =E2=80=9CMoving the border a few kilometers is not nece=
ssarily going to prevent Ukraine from launching drones and missiles at Belg=
orod,=E2=80=9D noted the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace=E2=80=
=99s Michael
Kofman. =E2=80=9CWhen they=E2=80=99re discussing a buffer zone, what they a=
re attempting to do is shift the line so that they can threaten Kharkiv and=
 force a partial evacuation, which would prove politically significant.=E2=
=80=9D Kharkiv is Ukraine=E2=80=99s second-largest city and, until the war,=
 was primarily Russian-speaking. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not the Russians=E2=
=80=99 intention to take Kharkiv, nor do they have the forces for it,=E2=80=
=9D Kofman explained. =E2=80=9CThe point is to draw Ukrainian forces to its=
 defense, fix their reserves there, potentially weakening the front line in=
 Donetsk for a Russian attack.=E2=80=9D

Russian troops are advancing quickly in part because they haven=E2=80=99t y=
et reached Ukraine=E2=80=99s main defensive lines, but also because the off=
ensive comes after key problems have been allowed to fester on the Ukrainia=
n side, both in Washington and in Kyiv. In Washington, it took seven months=
 to finally approve critical military aid for Ukraine, during which Ukraini=
an forces steadily ran out of
ammunition, both to shoot back at the enemy and to intercept the drones and=
 missiles attacking its cities and civilian infrastructure.

But, as I=E2=80=99ve written before ( https://puck.news/ukraines-got-its-61=
-billion-what-happens-now/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBS=
CRIBERS+%285%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Kyiv=E2=80=99s problems aren=E2=80=99t all =
Washington=E2=80=99s fault. Volodymyr Zelensky dawdled on the politically s=
ensitive question of expanding the military draft, allowing the Ukrainian m=
ilitary=E2=80=99s manpower shortage to grow acute. Now that the draft law h=
as finally been signed and implemented (just this month), it will take many=
 more months to find these new soldiers, equip and train them, and get them=
 to the battlefield. In the meantime, Ukraine is uniquely vulnerable, and i=
t had long been expected that Moscow would take advantage of this window
to launch a new offensive. =E2=80=9CThe Russian military can see what every=
body else sees: Ukraine has a deficit of manpower and reserves to cover the=
 front,=E2=80=9D Kofman explained. =E2=80=9CTheir goal is to create a dilem=
ma whereby the Ukrainian military cannot reinforce the defense of Kharkiv w=
ithout weakening the front line elsewhere.=E2=80=9D

There is some hope in the West that Ukraine might be saved now that America=
n aid is flowing again. But, as Kofman told me, =E2=80=9Cthe supplemental i=
s not talismanic.=E2=80=9D It hasn=E2=80=99t helped with manpower=E2=80=94n=
or was it supposed to. It doesn=E2=80=99t help with the building of fortifi=
cations=E2=80=94and it wasn=E2=80=99t supposed to do that either. And it ce=
rtainly can=E2=80=99t do anything to help Ukraine address the systemic prob=
lems ( https://twitter.com/teoyaomiquu/status/1790132722142150741?s=3D46&t=
=3DP7_NIiWwHiqKHGjde4FjFA&utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%285%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&ut=
m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) within its own military, like poor communicat=
ion, training, cohesiveness, and the unwillingness to report bad news up th=
e chain of command. The supplemental, Kofman said, =E2=80=9Cwill help Ukrai=
ne avoid the worst-case scenario this year, but things are likely to get wo=
rse
before they get better.=E2=80=9D

Kremlin Musical Chairs

By law, a Russian president must form a new government after his inaugurati=
on. By custom, since Russian law is a hazy concept, the Russian president=
=E2=80=94who, for the last two decades, has almost always been Putin=E2=80=
=94has used the opportunity to reshuffle his friends and allies among the v=
arious ministerial positions. It=E2=80=99s a game of musical chairs in whic=
h demotions are masked as lateral moves, and in which a simulacrum of chang=
e at the top is used to paper over the fact that there is only a finite num=
ber of people Putin trusts with the ship of state.

And because loyalty is, for Putin, the key qualification ( https://podcasts=
=2Eapple.com/us/podcast/about-a-boy-the=
-story-of-vladimir-putin/id1709963682?=
utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F14%2F24%29&u=
tm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_=
medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12=
a ) for government service, he has a hard time getting rid of anyone for in=
competence. Such people are not fired but simply moved to another powerful =
(and lucrative) position, where he can continue to keep an eye on them.

This is why Putin removed Defense Minister Sergei Shoigu from his post on S=
unday and scooted him over to the National Security Council. Under Shoigu=
=E2=80=99s leadership, the Russian army failed to execute Putin=E2=80=99s h=
arebrained scheme to take Kyiv in 72 hours=E2=80=94or in the ensuing two-pl=
us years. The amount of corruption and theft in the Russian military meant =
recruits were poorly equipped after Russia began its =E2=80=9Cpartial mobil=
ization=E2=80=9D in September 2022=E2=80=94remember the video of a commande=
r telling the men to stock up on their wives=E2=80=99 tampons because they=
=E2=80=99re handy in treating bullet
wounds? Ammunition was often in short supply. Who can forget the late Yevge=
ny Prigozhin=E2=80=99s rants at Shoigu, asking him, crudely, where the arti=
llery shells were?

Prigozhin then led a march on Moscow to demand the defense minister=E2=80=
=99s ouster. Putin, with the help of Aleksandr Lukashenko, defused the imme=
diate crisis, then killed Prigozhin two months to the day he began his anti=
-Shoigu mutiny. But despite the allegations of corruption and ineffectivene=
ss, Putin left Shoigu in place. After all, Shoigu was a good friend=E2=80=
=94the two often vacation and partake in shamanistic rituals together=E2=80=
=94and a loyal servant.

But then, last month, several ultra-high-ranking military officials were ar=
rested for corruption and for taking eye-popping bribes. One of them, Deput=
y Defense Minister Timur Ivanov ( https://www.cnn.com/2024/04/24/europe/rus=
sian-minister-timur-ivanov-detained-bribery-intl/index.html?utm_campaign=3D=
The+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DTh=
e+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_=
action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), was a clos=
e associate of Shoigu=E2=80=99s. The noose was clearly tightening, and now,=
 eleven months after Prigozhin called for his firing, Shoigu is finally out=
, replaced with economist Andrei Belousov, who will work as the head beanco=
unter at M.O.D., making sure the generals and the bureaucrats don=E2=80=99t=
 steal quite as much, quite as openly=E2=80=94and that the artillery shells=
 get to the front.

This, of course, is classic Putin. =E2=80=9CPutin is someone who generally =
thinks that revenge is a dish best served cold,=E2=80=9D C.I.A. director Bi=
ll Burns said ( https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-66241564?utm_campa=
ign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F14%2F24%29&utm_conten=
t=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3D=
email_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) last =
summer at the Aspen Security Forum, and he=E2=80=99s right. Putin believes =
in punishment delayed, meted out slowly and deliberately, on his terms, on =
his timeline, and never under public pressure. Which is why Shoigu=E2=80=99=
s firing may have seemed like a surprise to anyone who thought Putin had mo=
ved on and forgiven. He never really does.

The real surprise, though, was the ouster of Nikolai Patrushev as the head =
of Russia=E2=80=99s National Security Council. Patrushev, a silovik=E2=80=
=99s silovik, was a K.G.B. man like Putin and shares many of Putin=E2=80=99=
s hard-line, paranoiac=E2=80=94and increasingly millenarian=E2=80=94views o=
f the world. He was a member of Putin=E2=80=99s innermost circle, one of th=
e very few people who knew about and encouraged Putin=E2=80=99s plans for c=
onquering Ukraine.

And then, bam, just like that, he was out, replaced by=E2=80=A6 Shoigu.
(Today, it was announced that Patrushev would be one of the president=E2=80=
=99s special =E2=80=9Cassistants=E2=80=9D in charge of=E2=80=A6 shipbuildin=
g.) This one really puzzled me, so I called my good friend Mikhail Zygar, a=
n immaculately connected Russian journalist and author of All the Kremlin=
=E2=80=99s Men ( https://www.amazon.com/All-Kremlins-Men-Inside-Vladimir/dp=
/1610397398?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F=
14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F6%=
2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60=
617da42abd12a ). Zygar, who now lives in New York (Moscow recently issued a=
 warrant for his arrest), has just started writing The Last Pioneer ( https=
://zygaro.substack.com/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%285%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBE=
RS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_=
term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), a Substack on the inner workings of
the Kremlin. It has quickly become my favorite and most
illuminating source on how that byzantine place really operates.

=E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re very close in terms of their point of view, but Pa=
trushev has a big personal agenda,=E2=80=9D Zygar explained when I asked hi=
m, essentially, Why Patrushev? =E2=80=9CEven though they share a worldview,=
 it=E2=80=99s a personal thing. As [Putin] gets older, he wants less and le=
ss that [others] burden him with their opinions. Patrushev is someone who i=
s constantly buttonholing him.=E2=80=9D This demotion, Zygar believes, is a=
 way of shutting Patrushev up. Shoigu, Zygar added, is another example of s=
omeone who is a kindred spirit but whose opinions Putin no longer values si=
nce he now envisions himself as the generalissimo. =E2=80=9CPutin needs few=
er and fewer people,=E2=80=9D said Zygar. =E2=80=9CYou can tell by all thes=
e arrangements that he doesn=E2=80=99t need people who will say anything to=
 him. He needs people who will listen, not talk. Putin is acting like someo=
ne who is fucking fed up with people=E2=80=99s opinions. He already knows
everything by himself.=E2=80=9D

Another interesting point here: Patrushev had been advocating for his son, =
Dmitry, who until Sunday was the agricultural minister. Patrushev apparentl=
y=E2=80=94and incredibly=E2=80=94told Putin that his son would make an exce=
llent prime minister. (Zygar has more on Dmitry Patrushev and the other =E2=
=80=9Cprinces=E2=80=9D of Russia here ( https://zygaro.substack.com/p/tsard=
om-episode-1?utm_source=3Dprofile&utm_medium=3Dreader2&utm_campaign=3DThe+B=
est+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Bes=
t+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_actio=
n&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) and here ( https=
://zygaro.substack.com/p/tsardom-episode-2?utm_source=3Dprofile&utm_medium=
=3Dreader2&utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F1=
4%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F6%2=
F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c606=
17da42abd12a ); don=E2=80=99t miss it.) Instead, over the weekend, the
younger Patrushev was promoted ( https://meduza.io/news/2024/05/13/gosduma-=
utverdila-desyateryh-vitse-premierov-pravitelstva-rossii-v-ih-chisle-syn-ni=
kolaya-patrusheva?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%=
285%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%28=
5%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=
=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) to vice premier at the same time that his father, P=
utin=E2=80=99s old friend Nikolai, was demoted.

This too, Zygar points out, is classic Putin: Putin the referee, who makes =
sure that no one sinks too low or rises too high. =E2=80=9CIn some ways, th=
is is a strengthening of the Patrushev clan=E2=80=99s influence,=E2=80=9D Z=
ygar said of
Dmitry=E2=80=99s promotion (along with the promotion of another Patrushev a=
colyte). =E2=80=9CIn that case, if you add something in this column, you ha=
ve to take something away from the other column.=E2=80=9D By demoting Patru=
shev senior, Putin was able to maintain an equilibrium and show that only h=
is own power is endless. This, Zygar explained, was a way to show both Patr=
ushev and everyone else in the system that, in the czar=E2=80=99s palace, =
=E2=80=9Cno one=E2=80=99s influence is unlimited.=E2=80=9D

That=E2=80=99s all from me this week, friends. I=E2=80=99ll see you back he=
re next Tuesday. Until then, good night. Tomorrow will be worse.

Julia

