kYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo4OD=
E3ODl9/494a0656ee51b4f6a890dd528755c96bbc78347fdb9630ce7942828af170c1eb" st=
yle=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">s=
igned a letter</a></u> to National Security Advisor <b>Jake Sullivan </b>(n=
otably, <i>not</i> to Biden) expressing their concern =E2=80=9Cabout the me=
ssage the Administration is sending to Hamas and other Iranian-backed terro=
rist proxies by withholding weapons shipments to Israel, during a critical =
moment in the negotiations.=E2=80=9D The intraparty tensions are still ther=
e behind the scenes, I=E2=80=99m told, but they=E2=80=99re no longer playin=
g out in full view.<br/><br/></li><li><i>Bowman vs.
Latimer</i>: One place the tensions are still playing out, however, is on t=
he campaign trail. In New York=E2=80=99s 16th District, Israel critic <b>Ja=
maal Bowman </b>is facing a serious primary threat from <b>George Latimer</=
b>, an Israel supporter. And yet despite the D.C. view of the race=E2=80=94=
that it=E2=80=99s a litmus test of voters=E2=80=99 appetites for the war=E2=
=80=94neither candidate seems inclined to make their position on Israel cen=
tral to their message. With just five weeks remaining until the primary ele=
ction on June 25, Latimer is mainly running on infrastructure, abortion rig=
hts, and support for Biden; Bowman is hoping to win a third term by focusin=
g on racial equality and by painting Latimer as overly moderate.</li></ul><=
