          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In the last few day=
s, Russian troops have launched an offensive in Ukraine=E2=80=99s Kharkiv r=
egion, advancing around 5 kilometers and seizing a few border villages alon=
g the way. None of this is surprising: Ukrainian forces have been shelling =
the neighboring Russian region of Belgorod for months, and Russian official=
s have been openly discussing creating a buffer zone to protect the territo=
ry and its residents. Troops have been massing on the Russian side for week=
s. The only thing left was for <b>Vladimir Putin</b> to approve the order t=
o move in. <br/><br/>The Kharkiv offensive is likely designed to achieve tw=
o parallel political and tactical goals. =E2=80=9CMoving the border a few k=
ilometers is not necessarily going to prevent Ukraine from launching drones=
 and missiles at Belgorod,=E2=80=9D noted the Carnegie Endowment for Intern=
ational Peace=E2=80=99s <b>Michael
Kofman</b>. =E2=80=9CWhen they=E2=80=99re discussing a buffer zone, what th=
ey are attempting to do is shift the line so that they can threaten Kharkiv=
 and force a partial evacuation, which would prove politically significant.=
=E2=80=9D Kharkiv is Ukraine=E2=80=99s second-largest city and, until the w=
ar, was primarily Russian-speaking. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not the Russians=
=E2=80=99 intention to take Kharkiv, nor do they have the forces for it,=E2=
=80=9D Kofman explained. =E2=80=9CThe point is to draw Ukrainian forces to =
its defense, fix their reserves there, potentially weakening the front line=
 in Donetsk for a Russian attack.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Russian troops are adva=
ncing quickly in part because they haven=E2=80=99t yet reached Ukraine=E2=
=80=99s main defensive lines, but also because the offensive comes after ke=
y problems have been allowed to fester on the Ukrainian side, both in Washi=
ngton and in Kyiv. In Washington, it took seven months to finally approve c=
ritical military aid for Ukraine, during which Ukrainian forces steadily ra=
n out of
ammunition, both to shoot back at the enemy and to intercept the drones and=
 missiles attacking its cities and civilian infrastructure. <br/><br/>But, =
as I=E2=80=99ve <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6I=
mRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dQZWQ4Tzk3ZmdtaXpOcl9ZLWdqTT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6=
Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdWtyYWluZXMtZ290LWl0cy02MS1iaWxsaW9uLXdoYXQtaGFwcGVucy1ub3c=
vP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKy=
UyODUlMkYxNCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlna=
HRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg1JTJGNiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFp=
bF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA=
2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIj=
o4NjQxMTR9/1b0a71befc92f186c66fd4e3d2482f7363b600eb379548039a591f3d60d88ac7=
" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sd=
f">written before</a></u>, Kyiv=E2=80=99s problems aren=E2=80=99t all Washi=
ngton=E2=80=99s fault. <b>Volodymyr Zelensky</b> dawdled on the politically=
 sensitive question of expanding the military draft, allowing the Ukrainian=
 military=E2=80=99s manpower shortage to grow acute. Now that the draft law=
 has finally been signed and implemented (just this month), it will take ma=
ny more months to find these new soldiers, equip and train them, and get th=
em to the battlefield. In the meantime, Ukraine is uniquely vulnerable, and=
 it had long been expected that Moscow would take advantage of this window
to launch a new offensive. =E2=80=9CThe Russian military can see what every=
body else sees: Ukraine has a deficit of manpower and reserves to cover the=
 front,=E2=80=9D Kofman explained. =E2=80=9CTheir goal is to create a dilem=
ma whereby the Ukrainian military cannot reinforce the defense of Kharkiv w=
ithout weakening the front line elsewhere.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>There is some =
hope in the West that Ukraine might be saved now that American aid is flowi=
ng again. But, as Kofman told me, =E2=80=9Cthe supplemental is not talisman=
ic.=E2=80=9D It hasn=E2=80=99t helped with manpower=E2=80=94nor was it supp=
osed to. It doesn=E2=80=99t help with the building of fortifications=E2=80=
=94and it wasn=E2=80=99t supposed to do that either. And it certainly can=
=E2=80=99t do anything to help Ukraine address the systemic <u><a href=3D"h=
ttps://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dQZWQ4=
Tzk3ZmdtaXpOcl9ZLWdqTT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS90ZW95YW9taXF=
1dS9zdGF0dXMvMTc5MDEzMjcyMjE0MjE1MDc0MT9zPTQ2XHUwMDI2dD1QN19OSWlXd0hpcUtIR2=
pkZTRGakZBXHUwMDI2dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU=
1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NSUyRjE0JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1UaGUrQmVzdCsl=
MjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODUlMkY2JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG=
1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyY=
SIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjg4MTc5MH0/db4be8b9c2a4e7655606e7a6f853eba3263177308a2f057b=
ea628cbb90f27122" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:b=
old" class=3D"sdf">problems</a></u> within its own military, like poor comm=
unication, training, cohesiveness, and the unwillingness to report bad news=
 up the chain of command. The supplemental, Kofman said, =E2=80=9Cwill help=
